European Inflation Slide in Food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is due first and foremost to the sharp increase in the price of foodstuffs.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, registering - after 2.6 per cent of the month of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent - announced by the Union Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only gave as likely 3 percent - announced the Bloomberg.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian emitting banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, together with rising raw materials prices and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to 2%.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "there is a need to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, beat the 12-year record; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation was triggered in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
Wheat quotations increased by 88 per cent and soya quotation reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 per barrel black gold last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will fall from 2.1 per cent today to 2.5 per cent, but by 2009 it will decline to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during the year 2008.
