In many hospitals it saves with disinfectants
This year several thousands of infections produced first by the undue application of antibiotics have been recorded in hospitals.
The conditions of hygiene prevailing in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overloading of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the doctor-head of department of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, MRSA has been diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
An injured person from a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient shortly after returning to the hospital as a result of the MRSA infection, and since then there has been no major surgical intervention for the presence of bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, there have been 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance - said Karolina Böröcz, medical chief of department of the National Epidemiology Centre.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded, of the rest there is no information.
Nearly two thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacilin.
A third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria on their nose without causing any disease.
HS-produced infections (e.g. inflammation of the throat, amigdalitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once excessively or unduly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics are transformed into bacteria that are very resistant to antibiotics and quickly contagious in inappropriate hospital conditions.
They may cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicemia, first to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with weakened organisms, elderly people or people with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special in the MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotics Resistant
"These patients are isolated, nurses take care of them in rubber and mask gloves and there are the appropriate antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so, infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of training and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and homes of the elderly, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the diseases that carry the MRSA in their body.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also because the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come out to the public when MRSA infections are already occurring visible in the patient - said the doctor-head of the department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes rigorous mandates for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological patterns.
Antibiotic therapy should be directed, i.e. microbiological examinations should be undertaken to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
The taking of microbiological samples is even less common in the case of ambulant patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
He saves himself with the disinfectants.
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is contaged from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, they play a very important role in hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks, but also in this regard there are considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is contaged by drop transmission and direct contact between people, however, in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated for at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - said Karolina Böröcz - that in less favourable economic hospitals it is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a greater probability for infection.
In Karolina Böröcz's view, where appropriate preventive measures are implemented, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the pathogen agent's contagion may be stopped.
Government Programme against MRSA
Treatment of contagion with MRSA is a huge expenditure for the National Disease Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is combated.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The program appears to have successes, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a downward trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
