EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
The Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and the Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (BEI) Marta Gajecka signed in Budapest on Friday three limited credit agreements totalling EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructures as well as the energy sector.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget the transport and environmental protection projects, to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund subsidy, of which the parties had already signed a credit contract of EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed refers to the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement is also intended to finance the budget of educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective in Hungary, the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later, by extending the credit contract.
The parties signed a EUR 50 million contract for innovation, which the budget will mainly use for the Debrecen University's innovation and research project.
During the talks they also covered the theme of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
The agreement was reached that by the time Hungary finalized with the EU the details of the Metro funding, they will revert to the issue that whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this can take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed 113 projects in Hungary totalling EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the loans is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers an 8-year grace period, without charge for maintaining the credit at the disposal of the debtor.
