Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
As reported by the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, expert-level meetings will be concluded on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official opening of negotiations at the ministerial level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries of the world deliberate on the Bali Road Map, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
At present, there are lively discussions on the subject between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not yet wish to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to agree that, compared to the 1990 situation, greenhouse gas emissions will decline by 25 to 40 per cent by 2020.
Another major theme of the conference is that whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to provide material and technological assistance to countries in need of it.
A further agreement was reached on aid for developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a board of directors composed of 16 members, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit".
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020, whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed, and is prepared to commit itself to decreasing even by 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also ready to undertake commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capacities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries signatories to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed themselves to decline by 5.2 per cent, in this context the then 15 EU Member States committed themselves to comply with a 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent over the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will comply with - notes the press release from the Ministry of the Environment.
Much is at stake in Bali, since two years will have to sign the international agreement on long-term climate policy, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed by after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need of which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the international scientific association of the UN dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would lead to a delay in reducing emissions and could not prevent an increase of more than 2o C of the Earth's average temperature, which, according to scientists, would have countless and irreversible consequences.
The British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First, the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos on their actions against the Taliban - BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the general operating body of Kandahar, then sent to London to be charged to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings from Air Force soldiers who have been loaded to the Internet in this way and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in spring 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Community of British Nations (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had loaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the view of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the real objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional recruitment television spots - BBC was told by the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for being the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the relentlessly edited and censored recordings, the distributor also shows amateur videos, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "officiary" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak as much of loss, without yet presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, many videos recorded in real operations have been loaded on the Internet from the battlefields in Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only taking this opportunity lately.
Americans use a slightly different way to recruit with video games, free of charge, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put directly instead of the soldiers.
