The party isn't always written with red numbers.
In Hungary the law precisely defines the days that are written with red numbers in the calendar and has already become a generalized practice that around the holidays - that the next year will be less - the working days are reorganized.
Not even in the EU or in North America are parties united.
Hungarian laws make a difference between national party, state party and holidays.
The holidays are mainly related to religious and historical ephemeral holidays.
We celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is a holiday - the latter especially so that those who spent the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven parties written with red numbers in the calendar.
It is a national festival on March 15 in memory of the revolution of 1848 and October 23, a commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrated the foundation of the State, on May 1st, the work party, on November 1st and November 2nd, we remembered our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, in our country are two-day feasts of the Easter of Resurrection, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so it often becomes a bridge when before or after the party there is only one working day.
In exchange for long weekends like this, on previous Saturdays you cannot leave work or school.
It is the Minister of Labour who regulates in his specific decree when you have to work exactly in exchange for the day directly preceding or after the party.
This legal rule is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
It is not mandatory on the other hand for companies and service institutions that, due to their function, work continuously even during holidays.
This year the work order can be altered only around the end of the year: from December 24, life in the country is virtually stopped, since according to experiences, most people "does bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
The next year several of our holidays will coincide with mid- or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
First, the agenda will be changed around the work party so that workers can rest later for four successive days.
Saturday, April 26 will be working day, so that in return on Friday 2 May it will be a holiday day.
The other change relates to the party of October 23: on Saturday, October 18, we will have to work instead of Friday 24.
On the other hand, the year to come during the end of the year will be able to rest, since from December 24 it will not work almost anywhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
