A Heavy Memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archive documents, stored over 27 km of shelves to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far consultable only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of an old victim or his rightful owners.
The eleven States responsible for its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to searchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Reasonable information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow searches " particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers " , explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominative documents, owing to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Just as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
Records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after war for a practical purpose: to find deported or forced labour and, eventually, to provide proof of their detention, in order to open the way for compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
" There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents, " said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Anti-Semitism Search Centre at the Technische Universität of Berlin in 2006.
