Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which entered into force 1 November
In parallel with its parliamentary procedure, which ended today with the Congress's vote on the amendments incorporated into the draft in the Senate, the Government has submitted to public hearing the regulations that will develop the new law, with the aim that they both enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by deputies and senators to negotiate and agree on the best rules in order to ensure investor protection and to regulate in detail the activities of the entities in order to ensure efficient functioning of the markets.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, means the modernisation of financial markets, while reinforcing the protection of investors, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and fostering cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new regulation will allow financial advisory services to be provided to specialized firms as well as to natural or legal persons and create a new type of financial services firms (ESISs), financial advisory companies (FIAs), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio managers.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the implementation of operations on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are combined with multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also obliges investment firms to disclose on the market information on the key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management and requires them to keep a record of all their transactions, in order to facilitate the supervision by CNMV.
