Venus Climate can give an idea of the future of Earth
Venus may have once been an appropriate place for life, scientists declared yesterday.
Data from a European orbited spacecraft showed the planet more similar to a Earth twin than had previously been observed.
Venus is the nearest planet to Earth.
The two planets are similar in size and occupy similar orbits, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made the Earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus to a very different type of development.
