Venus: twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most like Earth, something that has not been raised so far. The European "Venus Express" probe discovered rays in the atmosphere and swivels in the poles, the same ones that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades now, researchers suspected that there could be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new tests: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays are silent at a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, the rays caused life on Earth: the storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it's not like that: if there was ever a life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, on the Venus surface there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface temperatures of 500°C reign, fluctuating in such a way that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Possibly, Venus is a "devil" twin from Earth, but he remains a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles of "Nature", according to the opinion of the researchers, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with the Earth than we had imagined," reports ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon recalls the wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost so large.
This planet also called dawn star or evening star orbit around the Sun almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: a day in Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not resemble the Earth much, scientists leave the base that both planets had formed in the same conditions.
On the two planets, water had been agglomerated and on earth remained in the oceans, but in Venus it dissolved into the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, in Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
