Most of the ninety-four Brillo-Box "type" on this list are fake.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Brillo-Boxes in 1968 by Andy Warhol, the Museum Moderna Museet in Stockholm conducted internal investigations and reached disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the Pontus Hultén museum gave to the Museum Moderna Museet, are false, and almost a hundred of the other "Type Stockholm", which are in circulation in the international art market, are also proven.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted the wooden boxes of red, blue and white, with the same sample that they had "Brillo" soap powder cartons.
According to Warhol, in the exhibition of his 1968 works at the Museum Moderna Museet were exposed hundreds of Brillo-carton boxes. These were not made by Warhol (because of the expenses), but were brought directly from the "Brillo" cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but exemplaries (which were just objects) exposed.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed the production of wooden shining boxes in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Museum Modern Museet.
Witnesses of those times now talk about almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as originals of the "Brill-Boxes" of "Type Stockholm" authorized by Andy Warhol.
Some of them were purchased at auctions for over $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the Pontus Hultén museum made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But in fact, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At this time Warhol had already died for three years.
Lars Byström, the head of the conservatives of the Modern Museum Museet, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. First they printed and smelted their tight silvers and then painted them to the oil with the brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the copies of the year 1990 shows that the painting was applied with a roller without printing the pressed silvers directly. Furthermore, it is not the oil painting, but the acrylic paint.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and must be removed from the official list of Brillo-Boxes by Andy Warhol," says Lars Nittve, director of the Modern Museum Museet and adds that if the Authentication Commission "Andy Warhol Art" in New York will not reach any conclusion, the Modern Museum Museet will classify these six boxes as copies/exhibition objects."
Already in July The Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these "great accusations" involving soap powder boxes.
But from that moment on everything remained in absolute silence.
